Quarantine: Night 2 

After 30 hours of travel time..

One very tired baby..

One emotional mumma..

We have arrived at our accommodation at the Gold Coast.

Room:1402

I was an emotional wreck arriving down here by bus with Corey on my lap..

Afraid of this journey and being isolated in a confined room I won’t lie I really struggled on my first night. 

Thankfully I have so many wonderful people who have helped get me here. 
I am grateful to be one step closer to Darren so we can be re United.. Today he dropped items off for me and Corey and I got to see him from the window. 🥰

Our room has no balcony and no fresh air as the windows are locked so getting used to air con will be hard button the plus side  we do have a bath and enough space for me to play and eat with Corey.

POSITIVES FOR TODAY
1. . I got to see Darren from my window!!! 🥰 
2.Corey had a relaxing bath today, so relaxing he fell asleep in it.
3. I have amazing parents who brightened up my day with flower a beautiful card and fruits and wine.

Tonight Corey and enjoyed our 1st Sunset together in Australia.

I had never shown any interest towards the press conferences held by the state authorities until  when Kerala was struck by a calamity. In the year 2018, when the state was hit by floods, I would sit in front of my laptop, eagerly waiting for the Chief Minister to address the media with the information he had that was valuable at such critical times. One day, while listening to him address the media, I noticed that his speech was filled with pauses. Though these pauses last only for a few seconds, I would be lying if I had said that they did not annoy me as a listener. Initially, I thought it was quite common to have pauses while delivering a speech in Malayalam. I also wondered whether this was common among  old-aged person while delivering a speech to an audience. But upon listening him speak, despite of several pauses in his speech, he maintained a calm demeanour while addressing the media confidently taking his own time to deliver his message loud and clear without any hiccups making me enlightened about the fact that being calm during turbulent times is a remarkable quality of a true leader. - Shamil

I have not watched "The King's Speech" in its entirety. But I have watched the movie in bits and pieces in Youtube. Narrating a tale of camaraderie between a King and his therapist, "The King's Speech" is based on a true story of how King George VI tries to overcome his stammering problem with the help of his therapist Lionel Logue and how the latter helps the king to make his first wartime radio broadcast upon Britain's declaration of war on Germany in the year 1939. Though the movie was released a decade ago, the climactic portions of the movie would still give me goosebumps that they would serve as an inspiration for me to prepare my speech for toastmasters. One evening, while watching the scene towards the climax when he delivers the wartime speech for a radio broadcast, the therapist hands him over the transcript of his speech with several places marked in red color for signaling him to pause while speaking. Though I have been in Toastmasters for a while, I had never understood the importance of having a pause on our speech until I heard myself speak.

"An idea can change your life" was the topic given to me by the host during the Table Topics contest which was held in a Toastmasters club a few years back. Ironically, I did not have any idea on what to speak then. The basic objective of the Table Topics was to think on one's feet. But, I was not even able to move a muscle under the glare of the audience that I spurted out some words in quick succession leaving them baffled. After the session got over, I did not stay in the hall for the break as I found it very difficult to face people after putting up a shabby performance. Upon reaching the hall, I found a small piece of paper folded neatly placed on my table among my other things. I picked it up and unfolded it to see a note from a senior toastmaster which read, "Try to pause while speaking. It shall keep you calm while enduring the storm".

EBPP Food Aid Supports Difficult Life in the Dry Season
By I Wayan S., 12th Grade Student, EBPP Manikaji School

My name is I Wayan S. and I live on the slopes of Mount Abang and am in 12th grade at the EBPP Manikaji School. My house is very far from the market and the path is steep uphill. For daily food needs, my family only relies on cassava, corn and spices crops from the fields. Because the conditions are very dry, we can only grow crops during the rainy season. The COVID-19 virus pandemic has made life very difficult for my family, because my parents can no longer work to earn additional money other than working as subsistence farmers.

During difficult times like now, I feel lucky, because every month at school I receive food aid from EBPP, and so far, I have received this aid four times. This assistance is very useful and eases the burden on my family’s life, especially during the dry season like now, and my family doesn’t have any more crops from the garden that can be sold.

I feel very touched, during difficult times like now, EBPP can still help people’s difficulties, and I would like to thank EBPP and all the donors who have helped me and all of my friends. Without the help of these groceries, my family life would become more difficult. Finally, I can only pray that all EBPP staff and donors are always in good health. Thank you.

"...As a sighted child, I was more likely to avoid physical contact with strangers. Instead, as much as I could, I looked at people from a distance and often made quick and certainly unfair judgments.
With increasing vision loss, I became much more aware of this introductory act of shaking hands."
When the lockdown was announced earlier in March this year, we decided to use the time to work on a blog in which we get a glimpse of the realities of kantharis and other associates from around the world. 

What challenges have come their way... How their particular beneficiaries cope with the new reality, and most importantly, what we can learn from this crisis and what we as kantharis can or plan to do, to realize a world 2.0, a world in which everyone counts.
This week Sabriye Tenberken (cofounder and catalyst, kanthari) laments the loss of the handshake – an important social tool for the blind and visually impaired.
To read the blog, please visit #linkinbio.

Bismillah, Bahan dasar Rockwool adalah terbuat dari bebatuan,  umumnya kombinasi dari batuan basalt, batu kapur Dan batu bara yang dipanaskan mencapai suhu 1.600 derajat Celcius sehingga meleleh menjadi seperti lava, dalam keadaan mencair ini, batuan tersebut disentrifugal membentuk serat-serat. Setelah dingin, kumpulan serat ini dipotong dengan ukuran yang sesuai dengan kebutuhan. Yang dirancang sebagai bahan peredam suara, isolasi terhadap panas, dan dapat juga digunakan sebagai media tanam hidroponik.
Rockwool tidak memakai tanah sama sekali. Wol batu umumnya digunakan sebagai substrat biakan hidroponik.
Selain bahan-bahan diatas, membuat rockwool juga bisa menggunakan bahan-bahan dari kaca, keramik, batu vulkanik dari gunung merapi dll. 
_sumber:wikipedia_
. 
. 
Alasan saya lebih menyukai pertanian hidroponik. Karena pertanian hidroponik jauh lebih baik dan sehat dibanding pertanian konvensional, karena penggunaan hidroponik salah Satunya akan mengurangi residu bahan kimia, bahkan nilai gizinya luar biasa. Sayuran yg dihasilkan dari pertanian hidroponik yaitu 150% lebih bergizi dari tanaman pertanian kovensional. Untuk perawatannya pun cukup mudah dan sangat cepat. Bahkan jarang terkena hama. 
Jadi, itu alasan saya lebih menyukai hidroponik, sangat menguntungkan dan sangat mudah. Yuk ikutan @octaviiaandinii0510

node.text:
The pension schemes dating back, for example, four years ago, is something to talk about. Today things have changed. 

Most savers don’t buy a pension and sometimes pay guaranteed income when they want to start cashing their money. And instead, they prefer to take money directly from their savings. 

This is an excellent idea for many people, especially if you have a good investment in place at this particular stage in life. In the first phase, you are focused on investing huge savings as possible. 

This is also known as the accumulation phase, according to financial advisers. The second phase –sometimes called decumulation refers to a saving where you can save and even invest further capital, but also withdrawing incomes from the savings. 

The two phases are quite different scenarios, but don’t mean you need a different investment plan before and after retirement. 

For many people, it is possible to primarily choose the investment with capital growth that will generate income in future dates. 

Similarly, an investment that creates a good amount of income is also a perfect option for growth as you will be able to reinvest money back to your savings.

Jag som småföretagare har varit evigt tacksam för hur Sverige har gjort både innan och efter anhöriga insjuknat i covid. (Alla dom har överlevt) och jag bara är så övertygad om att vi gjort rätt i ett hemskt kaos. Men vi har ju alla olika synsett och utgångspunkter. ❤️

I’m Santiago Chirino, an advocate for common philanthropy, a student of many subjects, and a son of humanity living in Ciudad de Mexico, Mexico. Through my youth, I’ve lived and visited many places, I had the blessing of meeting people from all walks of life. I’m just a common man, trying to find a path to help my fellow humans, and thanks to all of that, now I find myself as a beginner, amateur author, who pretends with some luck to make the world a better place. To participate in a project such as this, is a kind of activity that makes you stop and reflect on the life of everyone around you. Therefore, after I accepted the invitation Nana Iavorschi Cnejevici made me, to participate in this book, I reached out to as many friends and family as I possibly could to ask them their views of the “COVID-19 crises” in order to reflect the feelings and sensations that not only I but rather everyone felt during this worldwide event. I hope that in my words and those of my fellow authors, the readers of this book find a sense of unity as that is the only hope that we as a kind have to overcome the challenges that the future hold on us all. We have come a long way as societies, but its now, after the 2020 pandemic experience that we have the chance to reflect on the mistakes and injustices we, as a civilization have committed, because it’s now with this sense of unity that we have the chance to change the course of the future. A better tomorrow is only possible through the care and respect for each other as for the environment that surrounds us. So, years apart from now, when the future generations look back to us and hopefully find this book, they’ll see how even though we live in many places and our lives are very different, in the end, our story is only one, the story of humankind, and that should be enough to make us unite and fight for the survival of the planet as we know it.

Imagine you were born in 1900.

When you're 14, World War I begins and ends when you're 18 with 22 million dead.

Soon the SpanishFlu appears, killing 50 million people. And you're alive, 20 years old.

When you're 29 you survive the global economiccrisis with the collapse of New York Stock Exchange, causing inflation, unemployment and famine.

When you're 33 years old the nazis come to power.

When you're 39, World War II begins and ends when you're 45 years old with a 60 million dead. In the Holocaust 6 million Jews die.

At 52, Korean War begins. At 64, Vietnam War begins and ends when you're 75.

A child born in 1985 thinks his grandparents have no idea how difficult life is. 

Today we have all the comforts in a new world, amid a new #pandemic. But we complain because we need to wear masks. We complain because we must stay confined to our homes where we have food, electricity, water, wifi, Netflix! None of that existed back in the day. But humanity survived those circumstances and never lost their joy of living.

We should be thankful for what We have.

Saw this eye catching building yesterday and mused on something I’d read by Linda Poindexter about how 
“One small crack does not mean that you are broken; it means that you were put to the test and you didn’t fall apart.” 
It’s so true at the moment for all of us in this global pandemic and the effects will be long lasting but even as bits of our world close down again and localised restrictions are reintroduced there are also signs of normalcy - theatres, museums, galleries, gyms, bars and restaurants are all starting to reopen and people can travel and see friends and family. I know it’s easier sometimes to  paper  over the cracks in our lives but I’ve learnt in the long run they need to be exposed so you can learn from what caused them to be able  mend them and be stronger than before. Really hope our world learns, repairs and recovers quickly.

node.text:
In a time of collective but very varied suffering, it’s important to remember that the struggles of others don’t diminish our own challenges, and that conflicting emotions can and do co-exist. If you’ve worked through lockdown it’s OK to acknowledge that you’re exhausted, but also be glad you’re still in a job. It’s fine to feel sad that you can’t go on holiday, and also be thankful for your good health. Feelings don’t come one at a time politely waiting their turn!

Practising gratitude for the things you have works best *alongside* caring for yourself when you encounter your own difficulties and negative feelings. Through balance we maintain perspective and look after ourselves properly, which means we can better support others 🙏🏻

d o l l y  My earliest memories of hearing the sweet sounds of Country Musics undisputed Queen, Dolly Parton, would have to be as a small child in the very early 80’s. “Tie Our Love In A Double Knot” or “9 to 5” were the first songs that got me hooked on the big boobed, big haired, icon, leading to a life of adoration and idolisation. Country music runs deep in my veins, having been brought up on it via my parents and grandparents, however I briefly shied away from my love of country during my early teens and boarding school life ( Country was deemed daggy and you were terribly “Un-Cool” if you liked it ). Rediscovering my love for Dolly again at 16, Songs like “Coat Of Many Colours”, “Here You Come Again” and “Shattered Image” remain some of my favourites, her incredible song writing skills and Smokey Mountain, Songbird sweetness, providing me with a lifelong soundtrack. Her music has gotten me through some sad times ( “Wildflowers “ ), and some happy times ( “Baby I’m Burning ), somehow her voice always makes me feel good, especially during this whole Covid-19, stage 4 lockdown, pandemic mess! Helping me cope with feelings of homesickness and a yearning for the life of that young innocent, carefree child from the bush, Dollys voice is particularly soothing at the moment. So naturally my obsessions this week have turned to the original “Dumb Blonde”, and some of my favourite images of her over the decades.

BLOG: “They have all done something amazing and unique”
Director of Education in Liverpool, Jonathan James, reflects on today’s GCSE grades being issued to young people...

Thousands of young people will be receiving their centre-assessed GCSE grades today and I want to congratulate them all.

They have all done something amazing and unique, something no other young person has ever been asked to do: reached a significant milestone in their education in the face of a global pandemic. What a considerable achievement!

With the debacle around A Level results last week, on top of recent months, there has been a great deal of confusion and uncertainty. But the typical Liverpool resilience has shone through in our young people.

Issuing young people with their assessed grades is the fairest way possible – and we’ve seen this last week how fairness was jeopardised for so many. Hopefully, this move will also mark a greater trust in the professionalism of our teachers and leaders.
